3. it is accomplished or not accomplished exception with reason

try {
  int a = 10/0;
} catch (Exception e) {
  System.out.println("Can't divide by zero " + e);
} catch (ArithmeticException ex) {
  System.out.println("Can't divide by zero " + ex);
}

The code will not compile so the task is not accomplished.
from the code:
catch (Exception e) { ... }      // general
catch (ArithmeticException ex) { ... }  // specific

the ArithmeticException is subclass of Exception. so the catch (Exception e) statement
will catch all the exception, including ArithmeticException. Therefore, the second catch becomes unreachable.
which causes Compile-time Error - "Exception ArithmeticException has already been caught".

So, the corrected code is, 
try {
    int a = 10 / 0;
} catch (ArithmeticException ex) {
    System.out.println("Can't divide by zero " + ex);
} catch (Exception e) {
    System.out.println("Some exception occurred " + e);
}
